<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870402-0146 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:Don't VitiateWorker Handbooks</HL><DD> 04/02/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LABOR </IN><TEXT>   &quot;The Hazards of Firing at Will&quot; (Manager's Journal, March 9) by Andrew M. Kramer was an interesting update on the issue. However, like many attorneys, he suggests adding a disclaimer to the employee handbook such as &quot;This manual is not a contract of employment and we retain the right to alter this manual at any time.&quot;    The purpose of a handbook is to assure employees that they will be treated fairly. In a nonunion company, the handbook may promise the kind of protection that a union would offer. My feeling is that employers should write policies and procedures that they are willing to live with, and omit the disclaimer. The benefits obtained by promising due process to employees are lost when the company adds a disclaimer. Employees are not that dumb.    Prof. Steven D. Norton   Indiana University   South Bend, Ind.</TEXT></DOC>